In Java (and other programming languages), comparing two strings with `==` is incorrect and can lead to bugs. The reason for this is that string references are objects and the `==` operator checks if both variables refer to the same object in memory, rather than checking their content. For example:

```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";
if (str1 == str2) { // This will evaluate to true even though they contain the same value!
    System.out.println("They are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("They are not equal.");
}
```

Instead, use the `.equals()` method to check whether two strings have the same content, regardless of which object contains the content. In most cases, you want to compare the values of your strings, not their identity as objects. Here's an example:

```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";
if (str1.equals(str2)) { // This will evaluate to true
    System.out.println("They are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("They are not equal.");
}
```

So, when should we avoid using the `==` operator while comparing strings in Java? Always. Use `.equals()`. As for the difference between these operators, `==` compares references, whereas `.equals()` compares contents. You don’t want to compare references because different instances of the same string may be created by the compiler or garbage collector. Using `.equals()` ensures that you correctly determine whether two strings are equivalent based on their characters alone.

